// The `prelude.store` sub-module: the project's durable key-value store — named values that
// outlive any single run. Where a handler's `var` is state WITHIN a run and `env` is operator-set
// configuration INTO a run, the store is state BETWEEN runs: any run reads what another wrote, the
// operator browses and edits the same tree in the console, and an AI reads a stored note back into
// its context. Keys are path-like strings (`"memos/2026-07"`); a `store` value is a PREFIX — a view
// of one subtree, plain data (`scope` narrows it), so an agent can be handed exactly the subtree it
// should touch. Values are ordinary Katari values: a document, a data value, a `file`, a secret
// (`string of private` seals at rest exactly like a secret env entry, and stays redacted at every
// user-facing boundary). Writes are last-write-wins; one project's runs are serialized, so two
// writers never interleave.
//
// Each operation is a `request` — part of the run's ENVIRONMENT. A program performs it; a handler in
// scope may catch it (the same mechanism that catches `prelude.throw`) to intervene — a test stub, a
// sandboxed subtree, a redirect. Unhandled, it escalates like any request to the run's OUTERMOST
// environment, the runtime itself, which MACHINE-ANSWERS it against the project's durable rows — it is
// never surfaced as a question to a human operator. The answer is durable, so a re-run during recovery
// observes the same value the first attempt did: the store is replay-deterministic.
//
// Storing a `file` JOINS its bytes to the project's FILE LIBRARY: the stored file becomes a project
// file (owned by the api root, listed on the console's Files page) that outlives the run that wrote
// it. Overwriting or deleting an entry NEVER frees a file — the store only forgets the reference; the
// file is removed by an explicit delete through the file API or the Files page, and a stored reference
// to a file that was explicitly deleted reads as `gone` (`prelude.files`' contract for any handle to a
// removed file).

@"A view of one subtree of the project store: the path prefix every operation resolves its key
under. Plain data, not a permission — `scope` narrows it, and handing an agent a scoped store is
composition, not enforcement."
data store(@"The path prefix; \"\" is the root." prefix: string)

@"The whole project store — the root view."
agent root() -> store {
  store(prefix = "")
}

@"A narrowed view: the subtree at @path@ under @target@ — the store's `cd`. Plain prefix
arithmetic, usable anywhere a `store` is."
agent scope(target: store, path: string) -> store {
  if (target.prefix == "") {
    store(prefix = path)
  } else {
    store(prefix = f"${target.prefix}/${path}")
  }
}

@"A lookup that found a value."
data found(@"The stored value." value: unknown)

@"A lookup that found nothing — distinct from a stored `null`."
data absent(@"The key that had no entry." key: string)

// One lookup's outcome. (Type synonyms take no docs.)
type lookup = found | absent

@"Read the value at @key@ under @target@'s prefix: `found(value)` or `absent(key)` — a stored
`null` is `found(null)`, so presence and value never blur. Pin an expected shape with
`json.validate[T]` on the found value."
request get(target: store, key: string) -> lookup

@"Write @value@ at @key@ under @target@'s prefix, creating or replacing the entry (last write
wins). Any value fits: a document, a data value, a `file`, a secret (sealed at rest). A stored
`file` joins the project's file library — it becomes a project file (visible on the Files page)
that outlives the writing run. Overwriting the entry does NOT free the file it replaced; a file is
removed only by an explicit delete through the file API or the Files page."
request set(target: store, key: string, value: unknown) -> null

@"Delete the entry at @key@ under @target@'s prefix; deleting a missing key is a no-op. Deleting an
entry that held a `file` does NOT free the file — it stays in the project's file library; remove it
with an explicit delete through the file API or the Files page."
request delete(target: store, key: string) -> null

@"A `list` entry: a key holding a value, directly under the listed prefix."
data leaf(@"The key, relative to the listed prefix." key: string)

@"A `list` entry: a path segment with more entries below it — descend with `scope`."
data branch(@"The segment name, relative to the listed prefix." name: string)

// One listing's element. (Type synonyms take no docs.)
type entry = leaf | branch

@"List what sits DIRECTLY under @target@'s prefix: a `leaf` per value-holding key and a `branch`
per segment with entries below it (sorted; a name that is both leaf and branch yields both). The
file-system face of the tree — descend a branch with `scope`."
request list(target: store) -> array[entry]
